1
00:00:01,130 --> 00:00:04,170
Hey guys, let me ask you a quick question.

2
00:00:04,170 --> 00:00:10,280
Take a look at this chart with a 200 exponential
moving average and try to find out what determined

3
00:00:10,280 --> 00:00:15,730
the price to reverse right in this area and
was unable to move higher?

4
00:00:15,730 --> 00:00:21,090
What hides there and what is so important
in that area that made the price reverse and

5
00:00:21,090 --> 00:00:23,839
go the other way?

6
00:00:23,839 --> 00:00:29,000
You could say that this is an area of resistance
from the previous swing, and you would not

7
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:30,499
be wrong.

8
00:00:30,499 --> 00:00:34,070
But there also something else hiding around
that area.

9
00:00:34,070 --> 00:00:41,460
And that’s another variation of a 200 moving
average, and more specifically the 200 Hull

10
00:00:41,460 --> 00:00:43,550
moving average.

11
00:00:43,550 --> 00:00:49,140
And here it is, a perfect short opportunity,
at an area of confluence, with the previous

12
00:00:49,140 --> 00:00:52,579
swing and the 200 Hull moving average.

13
00:00:52,579 --> 00:00:58,960
I‘m sure that many of you don’t use other
types of moving averages besides the simple

14
00:00:58,960 --> 00:01:04,809
and exponential ones, but in this video, we’ll
discuss about the other moving averages you

15
00:01:04,809 --> 00:01:10,409
should start paying attention to if you want
to spot this kind of areas on your charts.

16
00:01:10,409 --> 00:01:17,950
So, the moving average is probably the most
well-known and heavily used indicator in technical

17
00:01:17,950 --> 00:01:24,859
analysis because it effectively captures the
trend in an easily identifiable manner.

18
00:01:24,859 --> 00:01:29,689
Moving averages are used to calculate the
average value of the price over a determined

19
00:01:29,689 --> 00:01:34,869
period of time and are extremely popular among
trend following traders.

20
00:01:34,869 --> 00:01:39,950
Here are the main moving averages used by
traders:

21
00:01:39,950 --> 00:01:43,859
Simple moving average – SMA
The simple moving average (SMA), the most

22
00:01:43,859 --> 00:01:50,979
common one, represents an average of the closing
price over a specified number of periods.

23
00:01:50,979 --> 00:01:57,219
The simple moving average is more stable and
signals the changes in price movements in

24
00:01:57,219 --> 00:01:59,060
slow fashion.

25
00:01:59,060 --> 00:02:04,099
For you to see the differences between the
moving averages, we’ll plot these averages

26
00:02:04,099 --> 00:02:08,160
on the same chart and we’ll use a 50 period
in our analysis.

27
00:02:08,160 --> 00:02:12,121
Exponential moving average (EMA)
Then we have the exponential moving average

28
00:02:12,121 --> 00:02:13,121
(EMA).

29
00:02:13,121 --> 00:02:16,930
EMA gives a higher weighting to recent prices.

30
00:02:16,930 --> 00:02:24,950
The shorter the EMA’s period, the more weight
that will be applied to the most recent price.

31
00:02:24,950 --> 00:02:30,650
The calculation method of an exponential moving
average is much more complicated compared

32
00:02:30,650 --> 00:02:32,820
to a simple moving average.

33
00:02:32,820 --> 00:02:38,750
The most important thing to remember is that
the exponential moving average is more sensitive

34
00:02:38,750 --> 00:02:40,300
to the recent price dynamics.

35
00:02:40,300 --> 00:02:45,090
Triple exponential moving average – TEMA
Now, things begin to get interesting.

36
00:02:45,090 --> 00:02:48,370
Here we have the triple exponential moving
average – TEMA.

37
00:02:48,370 --> 00:02:54,360
The triple exponential moving average (TEMA)
seeks to reduce the lag of a typical exponential

38
00:02:54,360 --> 00:03:00,560
moving average by tripling the weighting of
recent prices.

39
00:03:00,560 --> 00:03:09,680
TEMA responds to market movements quicker
than the SMA or EMA.

40
00:03:09,680 --> 00:03:13,480
Then, we have the adaptive moving average
– AMA

41
00:03:13,480 --> 00:03:18,440
The adaptive moving average (AMA) was created
to improve the original exponential moving

42
00:03:18,440 --> 00:03:19,440
average.

43
00:03:19,440 --> 00:03:26,040
The adaptive moving average multiplies the
weighting of an EMA by a volatility factor.

44
00:03:26,040 --> 00:03:34,100
Thus, AMA adapts more quickly to the market
by signaling when volatility conditions change.

45
00:03:34,100 --> 00:03:39,870
Its main advantage over other moving averages
is the fact that filters the noise in the

46
00:03:39,870 --> 00:03:46,010
trend and automatically changes its speed
considering the market volatility.

47
00:03:46,010 --> 00:03:52,740
Then, we have the Hull moving average – HMA
Hull moving average (HMA), was developed by

48
00:03:52,740 --> 00:03:59,150
Alan Hull, is a fast moving average, responsive
and with reduced lag.

49
00:03:59,150 --> 00:04:06,880
Hull used several weighted averages in calculating
this moving average and claimed that this

50
00:04:06,880 --> 00:04:14,870
formula reduces market lag and increase smoothness
at the same time.

51
00:04:14,870 --> 00:04:18,940
Another type of moving average is the weighted
moving average – WMA

52
00:04:18,940 --> 00:04:25,620
The weighted moving average (WMA) was designed
to find trends faster but without whipsaws.

53
00:04:25,620 --> 00:04:32,410
The weighted moving average offers more relevance
on recent price moves and reacts more quickly

54
00:04:32,410 --> 00:04:39,350
to price movements than the simple moving
average or exponential moving average.

55
00:04:39,350 --> 00:04:45,590
And finally, the Jurik moving average – JMA
Jurik moving average (JMA) is used by some

56
00:04:45,590 --> 00:04:47,310
institutional traders.

57
00:04:47,310 --> 00:04:55,970
Jurik claims that the jma is a powerful adaptive
tracker that can smooth time series data with

58
00:04:55,970 --> 00:05:03,160
very a small lag, no overshoots and no oscillations.

59
00:05:03,160 --> 00:05:07,490
Traders use different settings of moving averages
for different reasons.

60
00:05:07,490 --> 00:05:12,410
Some are interested in the long-term trend,
others want to trade based on the short-term

61
00:05:12,410 --> 00:05:13,410
trend.

62
00:05:13,410 --> 00:05:19,180
The length input of a moving average depends
on the objectives of the trader.

63
00:05:19,180 --> 00:05:24,680
Shorter moving averages are used for short-term
trading while longer-term moving averages

64
00:05:24,680 --> 00:05:26,810
are used by long-term investors.

65
00:05:26,810 --> 00:05:34,060
Taking into account the length of a moving
average followed by traders, there are 3 categories

66
00:05:34,060 --> 00:05:38,400
of moving averages:
First is the long-term moving averages – 200EMA,

67
00:05:38,400 --> 00:05:40,610
365 EMA
The most common exponential moving average

68
00:05:40,610 --> 00:05:45,550
is the 200 EMA and many traders apply it on
daily charts.

69
00:05:45,550 --> 00:05:50,990
It is believed that many institutions like
banks, hedge funds, forex dealers are following

70
00:05:50,990 --> 00:05:52,940
this indicator.

71
00:05:52,940 --> 00:05:57,970
If we take a look at this indicator on any
currency pair, commodity, market index or

72
00:05:57,970 --> 00:06:02,389
even cryptocurrencies, we can immediately
see its value.

73
00:06:02,389 --> 00:06:05,730
Then, the medium-term moving averages – 50EMA,
100EMA

74
00:06:05,730 --> 00:06:08,980
Many traders prefer to use the 50-period moving
average (50EMA).

75
00:06:08,980 --> 00:06:14,870
This is considered a faster moving average
as fewer input periods are used.

76
00:06:14,870 --> 00:06:20,960
The primary effect is that this moving average
will react more to medium-term movements.

77
00:06:20,960 --> 00:06:28,150
50 EMA is considered one of the most effective
trend indicators, offering also dynamic support

78
00:06:28,150 --> 00:06:31,710
and resistance levels on a chart.

79
00:06:31,710 --> 00:06:34,800
Also we have short-term moving averages – 10EMA,
20EMA

80
00:06:34,800 --> 00:06:41,370
Short term mas are preferred by traders that
want to trade with current market momentum.

81
00:06:41,370 --> 00:06:47,330
The most common short term exponential moving
averages are 10EMA and 20EMA.

82
00:06:47,330 --> 00:06:54,699
These EMAs react the fastest to price movements.

83
00:06:54,699 --> 00:06:56,480
Fibonacci moving averages – 5,8,13,21,34,55,89,144
EMAs.

84
00:06:56,480 --> 00:07:02,820
Some traders often take their input values
for EMAs from the Fibonacci sequence.

85
00:07:02,820 --> 00:07:11,330
Most common Fibonacci-based exponential moving
averages are 5EMA, 8EMA, 21EMA, 55EMA, 144EMA

86
00:07:11,330 --> 00:07:14,639
and so on.

87
00:07:14,639 --> 00:07:18,800
Traders must keep in mind that exponential
moving averages are lagging indicators as

88
00:07:18,800 --> 00:07:21,500
they are based on past information.

89
00:07:21,500 --> 00:07:28,580
200MA will have a much greater lag compared
to a 50MA because it includes market prices

90
00:07:28,580 --> 00:07:29,650
for the past 200 periods.

91
00:07:29,650 --> 00:07:37,810
The short-term EMAs respond more quickly to
new price changes, but at the same time offer

92
00:07:37,810 --> 00:07:39,410
more false signals.

93
00:07:39,410 --> 00:07:43,940
So, a trader must find a balance when using
exponential moving averages.

94
00:07:43,940 --> 00:07:49,650
Choosing one of the types of moving averages
depends directly on the style and preferences

95
00:07:49,650 --> 00:07:51,310
of each market participant.

96
00:07:51,310 --> 00:07:58,229
A simple moving average responds more slowly
to new price changes, while exponential moving

97
00:07:58,229 --> 00:08:04,820
averages or weighted moving averages provide
a larger number of trading signals, many of

98
00:08:04,820 --> 00:08:06,300
which may be false.

99
00:08:06,300 --> 00:08:11,790
So, it all depends on your trading style and
your trading objectives.

100
